column248: I just kind of guessed and then if the payoff was good I tried to stick with the same technique

I liked to use the percentage bar because I feel it gave me a better understanding of what I was investing and how much I should expect back based on the bar to the far right. I tried to stay in a range of 60% -70% invested in asset A...no real explanation that just seemed to work well in the beginning so I stuck with it. It helped once I found out that I didn't have to invest in every period in case I was struggling finance-wise or whether I was prosperous (I realized this much to late though I believe). I liked to watch the multiplier bar and the bar to the far right and judge it from there...too much chance to base it on anything else. I realized looking at everyone else's didn't help much so I tried to ignore that.

I began by investing about 50% in both A and B. If I lost money  this stayed the same. Once I began to make money  I gradually invested less in A to protect the money I had earned while still giving myself a chance to earn more. Once I was at a satisfactory number (usually over $10)  I invested nothing in A so I could be sure not to lose my earnings.
I think the introduction can be a syncrnized screen on each computer instead of using the projector which is difficult for everyone to see.

i made my investment decisions based on the previous multiplier and the probabity that five out of ten times  the multiplier was likely to be less than 1.0  but i realize that was wrong. i understood the experiment well  i just didnt know the probability factor and how it plays into decision making.

This was a somewhat frustrating experiment because I did not know if there was a good strategy to use or not. It seemed like all I could do was guess on the asset return rate and hope for the best. I know Asset A had a higher return than Asset B but it seemed like more often than not it gave me a negative return rather than a positive one. I pretty much ignored Asset B because even though it guaranteed a positive return  it was not that much compared to the return of Asset A.
